Sports in Japan are a part of Japanese culture. Japan has many traditional sports such as sumo, judo, karate, and kendo. Also, there are sports which were imported from the West such as baseball, soccer, golf, and skiing. Sports are popular with both participants and onlookers. In Japan, sports groups are an important part of school life.

The Sun was born billions of years ago and started the process of nuclear fusion, releasing photons as it combined hydrogen atoms to form helium. Stars such as the Sun release huge amounts of energy over the billions of years they exist and their lifetime often ends in a spectacular explosion, the intense energy helping form new elements.

The lion is a large mammal of the cat family, and is often called the "king of the beasts". Lions are mostly found in Africa and in a small reserve in India. They can live in cool areas, very hot areas, or in thick forests. Today, many live in zoos around the world. In the past they lived in Northern India, Pakistan, Europe, and Arabia.

The roots of a tree carry food and water from the ground through the trunk and branches to the leaves of the tree. The roots that grow above the ground are called aerial roots. The trunk is the main body of the tree. The trunk is covered with bark which protects it from damage. Branches grow from the trunk. They spread out so that the leaves can get more sunlight.

"Stewardesses" is the longest word that is typed with only the left hand. A stewardess is a woman who is employed to provide meals for and otherwise look after passengers on a ship or aircraft. These days, we typically use the term flight attendant, which can refer to a man or woman that performs this job. What other words are typed with only one hand?

Indiana is a state in the United States. Its capital and largest city is Indianapolis. Other famous cities and towns include Bloomington, Gary, Ft. Wayne, South Bend, Evansville, Muncie, and Marion. People who live in Indiana or are from there are called Hoosiers. Indiana's state bird is a Cardinal, Indiana's state flower is a Peony, Indiana's state tree is a Tulip Tree.

Nowadays, phones are clever enough to grasp your physical surroundings. They can detect the size of a room and the presence of other people. Kids studying the Mesozoic Era would be able to place a virtual Tyrannosaurus in their home or classroom. The technology would even know when to display information about a scene depicted in a painting as you stroll through a museum.

Which do you think there are more of: stars in the universe, or grains of sand on the beach? There are more stars in the universe than grains of sand on the beach. Try to picture that! However, there are more atoms in a single grain of sand than either stars in the universe or grains of sand on the beach. Pretty neat, right?

"A friend is someone who knows all about you and still loves you." Elbert Hubbard was an American writer, publisher, artist, and philosopher in the late 19th century and early 20th century. He is well known for founding an Arts & Crafts community in East Aurora, New York called Roycroft.

"To be yourself in a world that is constantly trying to make you something else is the greatest accomplishment." - Ralph Waldo Emerson. Emerson was an American essayist, lecturer, and poet in the mid-19th century. He is well known as a champion of individualism, and for leading the transcendentalism movement.

If you use someone else's idea on your project, make sure to give them credit by mentioning their name. If you took the idea from a website, or a book, put the website's address or the book's name. This is called citing a source. Citing a source is how you can include someone else's text in your project without getting into trouble.

Jefferson was selected by George Washington as the first Secretary of State. Jefferson thought that the federal government should be small. He had the opposite view of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton about the federal government. Jefferson ran for president against John Adams. He got the second highest number of votes and as was the law at the time, became vice-president.

Pride and Prejudice is a piece of classical literature by Jane Austen. The story is so popular that it has been made into a movie not once, but twice. The book depicts a high born gentleman Mr. Darcy who falls in love with a young woman Elizabeth. Elizabeth comes from a family far beneath him socially. The couple must overcome many obstacles to finally realize their desire to marry.

Virtual reality games are different from ordinary games. Players don't look at a phone or TV screen when playing. Instead, they put the virtual reality device on their heads and over their eyes. These devices are called headsets. They close you off from the real world and make you feel like you are inside the game.

Humans have more than five senses. Although definitions vary, the actual number ranges from 9 to more than 20. In addition to sight, smell, taste, touch, and hearing, which were the senses identified by Aristotle, humans can sense balance and acceleration, pain, body and limb position, and relative temperature.

The marine environment supplies many kinds of habitats that support life. Marine life depends on the saltwater in the sea. Marine habitats can be divided into coastal and open ocean habitats. Most marine life is found in coastal habitats, even though the shelf area occupies only 7% of the total ocean area.

Hairdressers help people cut, color, and style their hair. Qualified staff are usually called "stylists". Most hairdressing businesses serve both male and female customers. Male hairdressers who cut men's hair using a buzzer and a pair of scissors are often called barbers. The prestige of the job has been steadily growing over the past years.

The Electoral College consists of 538 electors. A majority of 270 electoral votes is required to elect the President. Your state's entitled allotment of electors equals the number of members in its Congressional delegation: one for each member in the House of Representatives plus two for your Senators. The president of the USA gets elected every four years.

Can you imagine standing on top of your food to taste it? Well, that's how many butterflies taste their food! Butterflies have taste receptors in their feet, unlike humans, who taste with their tongues. Butterflies will taste a leaf before laying their eggs to see if it will be good food for the caterpillars when they hatch.

When doing research, always look at more than one source. Each website, book, magazine, or newspaper represents a different source. If they all say the same thing, you will know it's probably true! A good number of sources to aim for is 3. Try to find 3 sources that agree on the same information any time you research something.

The continent of Africa is possibly the most language diverse place in the world. There are estimated to be between 1,500 and 2,000 languages spoken in Africa. In Nigeria alone, a country in Africa, there are over 500 languages spoken! Some of these languages are quite widespread, while others are spoken by a very small population.

The longest continental mountain range in the world, the Andes, is located in Chile. The Andes are about 7,000 km (4,300 mi) long. Approximately 80% of the country of Chile is made up of mountains. The mountains extend through the entire length of the country, which results in only 3% of its land being fit for agricultural use.

There are many types of exercises that can help keep you healthy and strong. Flexibility exercises help the human body in general, and in particular, help it to be able to reach farther and bend better. Aerobic exercises, like running, help the body work hard for a long time. Anaerobic exercises, like lifting weights, make muscles stronger.

The first four planets in our solar system, starting from the Sun, are Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars. They are known as the inner planets, or as the terrestrial planets because they are made mostly of rock and metal, and they are largely solid. Of the inner planets, Earth is the largest, and the only one that has extensive regions of liquid water.

Information is how we learn about things. Information can be pictures, videos, or words about something or someone. Did you know that when it comes to people, not all information is the same? There are two types: personal and private. Personal information might describe your likes and dislikes, while private information identifies you as a person.

Chuseok is a three day celebration and is one of the most important holidays in Korea. Chuseok is a harvest holiday, similar to Thanksgiving in the United States of America or Canada, and is held near the autumnal equinox. Family members from near and far come together to share food and stories, and to give thanks to their ancestors.

China is the fourth largest country in the world (after Russia, Canada, and the United States of America). It has an area of 3,719,275 square miles (slightly smaller than the U.S.) and its borders with other countries total more than 117,445 miles. As of 2013, China's population is 1.357 billion, or 1,357,000,000.

The Falkland Islands are an archipelago off the coast of Argentina in the South Atlantic Ocean. They have about 167 sheep for every person that lives there! The total population of the islands is about 3,000 people, and there are over 500,000 sheep. As you might guess, wool is a major export from these islands. You can also find penguins there.

A cloud is a large collection of very tiny droplets of water or ice crystals. The droplets are so small and light that they can float in the air. A cloud can weigh more than a million pounds. Clouds are white because they reflect light from the sun. Gray clouds become so filled with water that they don't reflect light.

The Koreas are located in northeast Asia. In 1945, they split into two countries: North Korea and South Korea. The tension between the two eventually led to the Korean War in 1950. Korea is a peninsula. There is a lot of fish in Korean cuisine. Korea was an agricultural society until recently, which explains the amount of rice in Korean diet.

A web developer is a programmer who specializes in the development of the World Wide Web. Developers often work in teams, but it is not uncommon to find a developer who works independently as a consultant. Web developers have to learn many programming languages to ensure a website is visually appealing, as well as fully functioning.

The Old Man and the Sea is the most famous work written by Ernest Hemingway. The story is centered around an old Cuban fisherman Santiago, who spends 84 days fishing without catching anything. On the 85th day, his bait is finally taken by a big fish he believes to be a marlin. The story describes the fisherman's battle with the marlin and his journey back to the shore.

In areas with seasonal climate, wood produced at different times of the year may alternate light and dark rings. In temperate climates, and tropical climates with a single wet-dry season alternation, the growth rings are annual, each pair of light and dark rings being one year of growth. In areas with two wet and dry seasons each year, there may be two pairs of light and dark rings each year.

Around 70% of the Earth's surface is covered by oceans. The deepest known area of the Earth's oceans is known as the Mariana Trench. Its deepest point measures 6.8 miles or almost 11 kilometers deep! This spot is called the Challenger Deep. It is located in the western Pacific Ocean, to the east of the Mariana Islands.
